<bioghist encodinganalog="545$a">
<head>Biographical Information
</head>
<p>Otti Y. Herman Windmueller was born in Borghorst, Germany August 16, 1916 to an upper middle class Jewish family.  After graduating high school, Nazi law dictated that as a Jewish woman she could receive no further education.  Windmueller was determined, and found a non-Jewish yet sympathetic dress maker to take her on as an apprentice.  She completed her three year apprenticeship and rose to assistant designer by 1938.  Her older brother, Wilhelm, had just relocated to Johannesburg, South Africa and Otti was eager to follow him.  When Fred Windmueller proposed to her she said yes on the condition they follow her brother.  Fred already had family in Richmond, Virginia with visas to arrive in the United States.  The border to South Africa closed and made their decision for them.  In 1938, the newlyweds, knowing each other for less than two months, boarded the S.S. Volendam.  Krystalnacht was six months later.  Otti's two sisters escaped to England, and later moved to America.  Their parents were murdered in concentration camps.  She reunited with her family and made the oral history based on family interviews in 1991 which can be found at the Jacob Radar Marcus Center of Jewish American Archives, part of the Cincinnati campus of Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion.  Her husband Fred, who was the Temple Archivist for Beth Ahaba in Richmond, originated the Windmueller Family Chronicle which also documents their departure from Germany.</p>
<p>Once in Richmond, Otti found what work she could as a seamstress while attending Richmond Professional Institute.  She earned a BA in Fine Arts.  In 1953 she became a part-time instructor in the Fashion Department.  Thus began her forty year career at RPI then VCU in the Fashion Department.  She was known for bringing her European flair to the design, set up several study abroad trips for the students, brought couture designers to VCU to lecture and contributed her in depth knowledge of pattern making.  She was the Chair of the department from 1965 to 1976, after which she stepped down to teach full time again.  In 1993 she was named Professor Emerita and established the Otti Y. Windmueller Scholarship.  After her retirement she continued her involvement with the university through volunteer work with VCU and MCV.  Otti Y. Windmueller died December 12, 2001.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
<head>Scope and Content
</head>
<p>This collection chronicles some of Otti Y. Windmueller's accomplishments at VCU's Department of Fashion as well as personal correspondence with friends and family and the story of her survival as young Jewish Woman in Nazi Germany as portrayed in the articles about and interviews with Windmueller, spanning from 1951 to 1994 with the majority of materials dating from the 1980s and early 1990s.</p>
</scopecontent>
<arrangement encodinganalog="351">
<head>Arrangement
</head>
<p>The collection is arranged alphabetically, with exception to oversize, and is comprised of three series:  1. Correspondence and Documents, 1951-1994, 2. Photographs, 1980s-1994, 3. News clippings, 1980s-1990s.
</p>
</arrangement>
